Demystifying the Shell¶

                🤔🐚¶







https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual

History 📜¶

There are a number of different shells built around the POSIX standard:

  • sh Bourne Shell 1979, one of the first major shells
  • bash Bourne-Again Shell 1989, available on most Linux systems
  • zsh Z Shell 1990, default shell on MacOS (backward compatible with bash)
  • fish Friendly Interactive Shell 2005, A user friendly shell that works out the box
  • nushell A new type of shell 2019, uses strucutured data over strings ^^


Not POSIX compliant

Getting Started 🏁¶

In this tutorial we will be using bash.

The notebook has shell commands embed in it that can be run as we go.

Let's test this out by running the commands below!

Everything is a File 🗂¶

All I/O in Unix is a stream bytes exposed via the filesystem.

This means a common set of tools can used for everything

Write programs that do one thing and do it well. Write programs to work together. Write programs to handle text streams, because that is a universal interface.

Unix Philosophy - Ken Thompson


Well, most of it is

Ken Thompson inventor of Unix, and language B and Go

Handle Text Streams 🌊¶

The file descriptiors 0, 1 & 2 represent the standard I/O streams; stdin, stdout and stderr.

They can be redirected to another file with:

  • > (overwrite)
  • >> (append)

The operators can be prefixed with a descriptor to redirect that specific stream.

In [3]:
./stdin_and_stderr

Error: an error message sent to stderr
Info: some information sent to stdout

Questions 🤔¶

Modify the above command to

  1. Write stdout to file
  2. Hide stderr from the console
  3. Redirect stderr to stdout

Hint: /dev/null is a special file that discards anything written to it

In [4]:
./stdin_and_stderr 1>/tmp/out
./stdin_and_stderr >/tmp/out

Error: an error message sent to stderr
Error: an error message sent to stderr
In [5]:
./stdin_and_stderr 2>/dev/null

Info: some information sent to stdout
In [6]:
./stdin_and_stderr >/tmp/out 2>&1 
./stdin_and_stderr &>/tmp/out

Write Programs to Work Together 👬¶

Programs can be combined using the operators below.

Lists of Commands¶

  • ; run commands sequentially cmd1; cmd2; cmd3
  • & run command asynchronously cmd1 &
  • && run a command conditionally on another succeeding cmd1 && cmd2
  • || run a command if another command fails cmd1 || cmd2

Tip: a programs return code determines success or failure and is stored in $?. 0 indicates success.

In [7]:
./succeeds

Program succeeded
In [8]:
./fails

Error: Something went bang!
Program failed

Write Programs to Work Together 👭¶
Programs can be combined using the operators below.


Pipelines¶
    

  • | send stdout from one program to stdin of another.
    • 

  • |& send stdout and stderr from one program to stdin of another.
    •

Do One Thing and Do It Well 🗿¶
    

  • man - format and display the on-line manual pages
    • 

  • cat - concatenate and print files
    • 

  • tee - duplicate standard input
    • 

  • sort - sort or merge records (lines) of text and binary files
    • 

  • uniq - report or filter out repeated lines in a file
    • 

  • wc - word, line, character, and byte count
    • 

  • head, tail - display the first/last part of a file
    • 

  • grep - file pattern searcher
    • 



Stream editing¶
    

  • tr - translate characters
    • 

  • cut - cut out selected portions of each line of a file
    • 

  • sed - stream editor
    • 

  • awk - pattern-directed scanning and processing language
    • 



Non-Unix¶
    

  • pbcopy, pbpaste - provide copying and pasting to the clipboard
    • 

  • jq - Command-line JSON processor
    •

Exercises 🏋🏾‍♂️¶
Find all users in a log¶
The script you just ran did bad things to some users 


    

  • Can you find all logs for one of the affected users?
    • 

  • How many users were affected?
    • 

  • Can you get a list of all affected users?
    • 

  • Can you copy the users into your clipboard?
    • 
























Can you find all logs for one of the affected users?¶
























Tip Each request has a unique ID you might be able to search for





















In [19]:



     


grep "43898d94-3aa1-4557-bd07-6682f90bf8f2" script.log



     




















    
    






2022-12-03 21:41:45,969 - __main__ - INFO - [43898d94-3aa1-4557-bd07-6682f90bf8f2] Found MadGuineaPig (__main__.py:34)
2022-12-03 21:41:46,185 - __main__ - INFO - [43898d94-3aa1-4557-bd07-6682f90bf8f2] MadGuineaPig needs fixing (__main__.py:38)

2022-12-03 21:41:47,274 - __main__ - INFO - [43898d94-3aa1-4557-bd07-6682f90bf8f2] Fixing emotion (__main__.py:46)
2022-12-03 21:41:48,403 - __main__ - INFO - [43898d94-3aa1-4557-bd07-6682f90bf8f2] MadGuineaPig emotion successfully fixed (__main__.py:51)




























How many users were affected?¶


















In [20]:



     


grep "stuck in machine" script.log | wc -l



     




















    
    






       8




























Can you get a list of all affected users?¶


















In [21]:



     


grep ERROR script.log | cut -d' ' -f 9 | sort | uniq



     




















    
    






CalmBeetle
GladDragonfly
GladSeahorse
LividLemming
OrneryArcticFox
ScaredCoyote
WaryPorpoise
WearyFerret




























Can you copy the users into your clipboard?¶


















In [22]:



     


grep ERROR script.log | cut -d' ' -f 9 | sort | uniq | pbcopy



     























Exercises 🏋🏾‍♂️¶
For this exercise you will need jq


brew install jq



Parsing JSON output¶
The database command below returns entries from a database as JSON.


./db_query



    

  • Can you use jq to extract all the users with their creation date?
    • 

  • Can you filter the query above to show only active users?
    • 

  • Can you show all users who have an order with status 'ERROR'?
    • 





Tip: Checkout this jq cheatsheet https://lzone.de/cheat-sheet/jq

Show all users who have an order with status 'ERROR'¶


















In [28]:



     


./db_query | jq '.[] | select(.orders[] | .status == "ERROR") | {username} | join(" ")'
